to Rhinokey's [[Reckless driving|crazy driving]], he is banned from driving and therefore banned from the upcoming race.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=7\n |Title=Bumblelion and the Terrified Forest\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Ken Koonce,<br> David Weimers\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|10|26}}\n |ShortSummary=Bumblelion and Hoppo go deep into the Terrified Forest to rescue Butterbear from an evil witch.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=8\n |Title=Eleroo's Wishday\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Mark Evanier\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|11|2}}\n |ShortSummary=Eleroo wishes to fly using the wishing well.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=9\n |Title=Ghostrustlers\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Ken Koonce,<br> David Weimers\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|11|9}}\n |ShortSummary=With a plague in Wuz Town, the Wuzzles move to a [[ghost town]] that really ''is'' inhabited by ghosts.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=10\n |Title=A Pest for a Pet\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Mark Evanier\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|11|16}}\n |ShortSummary=The Wuzzles get revenge on Rhinokey for playing jokes on ''them'' by playing a joke on ''him'' that makes him depart from Wuz.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=11\n |Title=The Main Course\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Ken Koonce,<br> David Weimer\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|11|23}}\n |ShortSummary=After being attacked by pirats (part [[parrot]], part [[rat]]), the Wuzzles sail to an island where Hoppo is mistaken for a god by a tribe of pigmice (part [[pig]], part [[mouse]]) who intend to throw her into a volcano as a sacrifice.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=12\n |Title=Class Dismissed\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Ken Koonce,<br> David Weimers\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|11|30}}\n |ShortSummary=When Butterbear is hired to make invitations to a ball, the other Wuzzles decide to get invited by bettering their class. Also, Crocosaur makes a bet with Butterbear about turning Brat into a sensible and polite Wuzzle.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber=13\n |Title=What's Up, Stox?\n |DirectedBy=Fred Wolf\n |WrittenBy=Ken Koonce,<br> David Weimers\n |OriginalAirDate={{Start date|1985|12|7}}\n |ShortSummary=After visiting the new neighbor, zillionaire Tycoon (part [[tiger]], part [[raccoon]]), the Wuzzles are given a money tree which they obsess over. Crocosaur, however, plans to steal it for himself.\n |LineColor=000070\n}}\n|}\n\n==Legacy==\nButterbear and Rhinokey will appear in a future episode of ''[[DuckTales (2017 TV series)|Ducktales (2017)]]''. Unlike their original TV series, Butterbear and Rhinokey's designs are more realistic and animalistic.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/comic-con/2019/07/19/ducktales-rescue-rangers-talespin/|title='DuckTales' surprises Comic-Con with 'Rescue Rangers,' Lin-Manuel Miranda|website=EW.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{notelist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0088643|title=The Wuzzles}}\n* {{bcdb |Walt_Disney_Studios/Television/The_Wuzzles/ |The Wuzzles}}\n* {{tv.com show|the-wuzzles|The Wuzzles}}\n\n{{Children's programming on CBS in the 1980s}}\n{{Children's programming on the American Broadcasting Company in the 1980s}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wuzzles, The}}\n[[Category:1985 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1985 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:CBS original programming]]\n[[Category:1980s American animated television series]]\n[[Category:Fictional hybrid life forms]]\n[[Category:Disney Channel original programming]]\n[[Category:Fictional hybrids]]\n[[Category:American animated television programs featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney Television Animation]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy television series]]\n", "name_user": "Blazewing16", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wuzzles"}
{"title_page": "Unbalance+Balance", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Unbalance+Balance\n| type       = album\n| artist     = [[Akina Nakamori]]\n| cover      = File:Unbalance_Balance_(Akina_Nakamori_album_cover_jacket).jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = 22 September 1993<br />4 December 2002 (as ''Unbalance+Balance+6'')\n| recorded   = 1992-1993\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Victor Studio<br />Music Inn<br />Cherry Island Studio\n| genre      = Pop\n| length     = 42:47 (original)<br /> 72:46 (re-printed)\n| language   = [[Japanese language|Japanese]]\n| label      = [[MCA Records|MCA]]\n| producer   = [[Akina Nakamori]]\n| prev_title = [[Cruise (Akina Nakamori album)|Cruise]]\n| prev_year  = 1989\n| next_title = [[La Alteraci\u00f3n]]\n| next_year  = 1995\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Unbalance+Balance\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Not Crazy To me\n | single1date = 21 May 1993\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Unbalance+Balance''''' is the fifteenth studio album by Japanese singer [[Akina Nakamori]] and first studio album to be released during 1990's. It was released on 22 September 1993 under the [[MCA Records]] label\n\nThe album includes B-side ''Not Crazy To Me'' taken from the single ''Everlasting Love''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.universal-music.co.jp/nakamori-akina/products/umck-1149/|title=\u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc - \u30a2\u30f3\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9+\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9+6 - UNIVERSAL MUSIC JAPAN|publisher=[[\u30e6\u30cb\u30d0\u30fc\u30b5\u30eb\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af (\u65e5\u672c)|\u30e6\u30cb\u30d0\u30fc\u30b5\u30eb\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30c3\u30af\u5408\u540c\u4f1a\u793e]]|accessdate=2012-07-28}}</ref><ref name=\"cd.journal\">{{Cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/-/1193110571|title=<nowiki>\u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc / \u30a2\u30f3\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9+\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9 [CD] [\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0] - CDJournal.com</nowiki>|publisher=\u97f3\u697d\u51fa\u7248\u793e|accessdate=2011-04-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002 was released re-printed version of the album ''Unbalance+Balance+6'' which includes original version of ''Not Crazy To Me'', single ''Everlasting Love'', ''Yoru no Dokoka de'', and B-sides ''Rose Bud'' and ''Blue Lace'', which was previously unreleased in the album recordings.<ref name=\"cd.journal.plus6\">{{Cite web|url=http://artist.cdjournal.com/d/unbalance--balance--6/3202100819|title=<nowiki>\u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc / \u30a2\u30f3\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9+\u30d0\u30e9\u30f3\u30b9+6 [\u518d\u767a] [CD] [\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0] - CDJournal.com</nowiki>|publisher=\u97f3\u697d\u51fa\u7248\u793e|accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIt's Nakamori's first studio album to be released after 4 years and in new recording label.\n\nThe first production of the album started in summer 1992, after Nakamori finished filming television drama ''Sugao no Mama de''.<ref>Akina Nakamori (1993). Unbalance+Balance (CD Album; album notes). Akina Nakamori. Japan: MCA Records. GRCO-3001.</ref> According to recording producer, Nakamori's distanced from her casual style and along with new music production staff aimed more into contemporary style.<ref>{{cite book |title=\u30ed\u30c3\u30af\u30f3\u30ed\u30fc\u30eb\u30fb\u30cb\u30e5\u30fc\u30ba\u30e1\u30fc\u30ab\u30fc10\u6708\u53f7\u5897\u520a Queen's Pal |date=1993-10-20 |publisher=\u30d3\u30af\u30bf\u30fc\u30a8\u30f3\u30bf\u30c6\u30a4\u30f3\u30e1\u30f3\u30c8 |page=6}}</ref>\n\nSome of the past musical writers were involved with the album, including [[Takashi Matsumoto]], Makoto Sekiguchi from [[C-C-B]], [[Koji Tamaki]] from [[Anzen Chitai]] and Brasilian singer-songwriter Osny Melo. Among new team includes well-known names as [[Ryuuichi Sakamoto]], [[Nokko]] from [[Rebecca (band)|Rebecca]] and [[Tetsuya Komuro]]. Composer [[Akira Senju]] later become the main producer of the series of cover albums \"Utahime\".\n\nBy this album, Nakamori start be in the charge of the producing albums. It's her second self-produced album for the first time in 7 year.\n\nIt was Nakamori's idea to write two songs with same melody yet different lyrics: ''Eien no Tobira'' was written by Natsuno Serino and ''Kagerou'' by Nakamori herself. It's Nakamori's first original song for first time in 9 years.<ref name=\"qp\">{{Cite journal|journal=Rock n Roll News Maker October Issue Queen's Pal|title=page6|publisher=Victor Entertainment|date=1993-10-20|page=6}}</ref>\n\n''Aibu'' was later recorded as a B-side in the cover single ''Kataomoi'' in 1994.<ref name=\"oricon\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/prof/artist/235370/products/music/163507/1/|title=\u7247\u60f3\u3044 \u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc\u306e\u30d7\u30ed\u30d5\u30a3\u30fc\u30eb\u306a\u3089\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u82b8\u80fd\u4eba\u4e8b\u5178-ORICON STYLE|publisher=[[\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3]]|accessdate=2013-06-18}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\n===Single===\nIt consists of one previously released single.<ref>{{cite web|title=Discography (\u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc ) - Alteranet|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19990223182912/http://www.meix-net.or.jp/~akina/disco2.html#albums|website=meix-net.jp}}</ref>\n\n''Not Crazy To Me'' is B-side take from the twenty-seventh single ''Everlasting Love''. It was written by [[Nokko]] and produced by [[Ryuuichi Sakamoto]]. It was released on 21 May 1993. It was Nakamori's the first single to be released in two years under new recording label. It includes renewed melodical arrangement, compared to the original. The original version was included re-printed version of album, ''Unbalance+Balance+6'' and compilation album''Utahime Densetsu: 90's Best''.<ref>{{cite web|title=\u4e2d\u68ee\u660e\u83dc / \u6b4c\u59eb\u4f1d\u8aac\uff5e90's BEST\uff5e [3CD+DVD] [\u9650\u5b9a]|url=https://artist.cdjournal.com/d/-/4108010677|website=cdjournal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\u6b4c\u59eb\u4f1d\u8aac~\u201990s BEST [\u521d\u56de\u9650\u5b9a\u76e4]|url=https://www.universal-music.co.jp/nakamori-akina/products/umck-9196/|website=UMJ.jp}}</ref>\n\nThe single debuted at number 10 on the Oricon Single Weekly Charts.\n\nIt's Nakamori's final single to be released in compact disc format.\n\n==Stage performances==\nWhile the singles ''Gekka'' and ''Aibu'' were performed in the later live tours and music television programs, the albums tracks ''Kurobara'' was performed in one-night live ''Parco Threatre Live'' in 1994, ''Norma Jean'' in live tour ''Spoon'' in 1998,  ''Eien no Tobira'' and ''Hikaru no Nai Mangeky\u014d'' were performed for the first time in acoustic live tour ''21 Seiki he no Tabidachi''. Kagerou was performed very often as well: Parco Theatre Live, True Akina Live in 1995 and acoustic live tour ''21 Seiki he no Tabidachi''.\n\n==Chart performance==\nThe album reached at number 4 on the Oricon Album Weekly Chart charted for the 9 consecutive weeks with the sales of 186,600 copies.<ref>{{cite book |title=Oricon Album Chart Book Complete Edition 1970-2005 |date=25 April 2006 |publisher=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u30fb\u30de\u30fc\u30b1\u30c6\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\u30fb\u30d7\u30ed\u30e2\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3 |isbn=4871310779 |pages=3, 455\u2013457, 883}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|date=1995-08-07|title=\u30a2\u30eb\u30d0\u30e0\u30c1\u30e3\u30fc\u30c8|journal=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3\u30a6\u30a3\u30fc\u30af\u30ea\u30fc The Ichiban|volume=17|issue=|page=63|publisher=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.oricon.co.jp/search/result.php?kbn=ja&types=rnk&year=1995&month=7&week=5&submit5.x=16&submit5.y=18|title=\u691c\u7d22\u7d50\u679c-ORICON STYLE \u30a2\u30fc\u30c6\u30a3\u30b9\u30c8/CD\u691c\u7d22|publisher=\u30aa\u30ea\u30b3\u30f3|accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref> It's Akina's last studio album which sold over 100,000 copies.\n\nUntil 2002 cover album ''Zero Album Utahime 2'', none of Nakamori albums didn't debut at Top 10 in the Oricon Album Weekly Charts.\n\n==Track listing==\n===Unbalance+Balance===\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = \n| extra_column    = Arranger(s)\n